      <hedline>
        <hl1>KELLOGG SETTLEMENT</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By ANDREW MARTIN</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Martin, Andrew</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Five Days column; Kellogg Co announced it would stop advertising some of its most popular products to children under age of 12 unless foods met new nutrition guidelines, such as having no more than 12 grams of sugar per serving; photo (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>What's next, Marshmallow Fluff? The Kellogg Company announced that it would stop advertising some of its most popular products to children under the age of 12 unless the foods met new nutrition guidelines, such as having no more than 12 grams of sugar per serving.</p>
        <p>The new directive, which will be phased in over the next year and a half, affects some of the company's most popular products among children, including Froot Loops, Rice Krispies and Pop-Tarts.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>What's next, Marshmallow Fluff? The Kellogg Company announced that it would stop advertising some of its most popular products to children under the age of 12 unless the foods met new nutrition guidelines, such as having no more than 12 grams of sugar per serving.</p>
        <p>The new directive, which will be phased in over the next year and a half, affects some of the company's most popular products among children, including Froot Loops, Rice Krispies and Pop-Tarts.</p>
        <p>The announcement comes after years in which health officials have warned that the constant stream of junk-food ads aimed at children is adding to the incidence of obesity. Some members of Congress have called for federal regulation of children's advertising, while the industry has favored self-regulation.</p>
        <p>The question for Kellogg in the months ahead is whether the company can reformulate its products to meet the new guidelines and not ruin the taste. Kellogg's competitors, meanwhile, will feel increasing pressure to follow suit.</p>
        <p>ANDREW MARTIN</p>
        <p>FIVE DAYS</p>
      </block>
